Column references — the four ways.

Pyspark accepts four different styles for naming a column. They are mostly interchangeable, but each one has a place.

The first is a plain string — just the column name in quotes. It is perfect for a simple select, group-by, or sort. But it cannot apply functions or build expressions.

The second is col of the column name. This is for building expressions, and for passing a column into things like when, coalesce, or the sum function. This is the safest default.

The third is dataframe, square brackets, column name. Its main job is disambiguating columns when you join two dataframes that share a column name. It is a bit verbose for normal use.

The fourth is expr, with a sequel-style snippet inside — for example, expr of amount times zero point zero two. It is handy for pasting a sequel expression, but it is easy to typo, because the string is parsed at runtime.

So, rule of thumb. Use a string when the interface just needs a name. Use col when you are building an expression. Use dataframe square brackets when you are joining. And use expr sparingly.
